                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">551.5F1/147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-08-07T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 7, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>88. Legation’s 99, July 28, 5 p.m. Your proposal to have Germany present a
                    resolution on a silver conference to the League of Nations meets with our
                    approval. You should confidentially push it. Our Ambassador in Germany<note
                        n="54" xml:id="d481fn54">Frederic M. Sackett.</note> is being informed of
                    these proceedings but advised not to initiate anything. This Government attaches
                    great importance to the silver problem. Consequently, you should be very active
                    but discreet in the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
